## 2. Overall Description

### 2.1 Product Perspective
Amane is a standalone web application but designed to interoperate with its sister platform Selamta (for women-specific services). Both share:
- A common backend API
- Resource database (shelters, legal aid, counselors)
- Authentication layer (optional)

Amane does not depend on third-party platforms for core functionality but may integrate with:
- SMS gateways (for crisis alerts)
- OpenStreetMap (for location services)
- Jitsi Meet (for video counseling)

### 2.2 User Classes and Characteristics

| User Class | Description | Needs |
|-----------|-------------|-------|
| Survivor | Person experiencing abuse/violence | Anonymous reporting, emotional support, safety planning |
| Caregiver | Parent/guardian of a child survivor | Guardian reporting, child safety resources |
| Counselor/Advocate | Trained professional (NGO, volunteer) | Case management, secure communication |
| NGO Admin | Staff managing resources/events | Verify listings, post events, view anonymized analytics |
| Job Provider | Ethical employer in social sector | Post vetted job openings |
| General Public | Ally or awareness seeker | Read stories, attend events, learn about GBV |

### 2.3 Operating Environment
- Browsers: Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge (latest 2 versions)
- Devices: Desktop, laptop, tablet, smartphone
- Internet: Works on low-bandwidth; core features available offline via PWA caching
- Languages: Amharic (primary), Oromo, Tigrinya, English

### 2.4 Design and Implementation Constraints
- Must comply with Ethiopian data privacy norms (no explicit law, but follow GDPR principles)
- No persistent tracking (cookies, analytics) without explicit consent
- All user data must be encrypted at rest and in transit
- Must support offline use for key features (reporting draft, emergency contacts)

### 2.5 Assumptions and Dependencies
- Users have access to basic internet (even if intermittent)
- Partner NGOs will verify resource listings (shelters, legal aid)
- Voice/audio features assume device has microphone/speaker
- SMS integration depends on local telecom partnerships (optional in v1)

